, 			{
				"box" : 				{
					"id" : "obj-30",
					"linecount" : 21,
					"maxclass" : "comment",
					"numinlets" : 1,
					"numoutlets" : 0,
					"patching_rect" : [ 14.0, 795.0, 604.0, 288.0 ],
					"text" : "record <v> [<v> ...] — record one or more values in sequence. Symbols become node ids directly; ints and floats are stringified (\"60\", \"0.5\"). Each consecutive pair increments the corresponding edge count by 1. A multi-value message is equivalent to sending each value separately.\n\norder <n> — set the Markov order, 1 to 8. Clears the context window. Nodes learned at another order remain untouched in the graph (a 1-gram node \"a\" and a 2-gram node \"a|b\" never collide).\n\nforget — clear the sliding context window without touching the graph. Send at phrase boundaries so the last value of one phrase doesn't link to the first of the next.\n\nnormalize [prob|cost] — destructive conversion of the target graf's edge weights, per node. prob (default): weights become probabilities summing to 1 per node, ready for graf.traverse mode random. cost: weights become -log(p), ready for mode dijkstra where shortest path equals most probable path. Counts are destroyed either way; recording afterwards mixes scales.\n\nbang — post observer state (target graf, order, current context window) to the Max console. Debugging aid.\nObject arguments (creation, not messages): [graf.observe <grafname> [<order>]] — name of the graf instance to write into (required), initial Markov order (optional, default 1).\n\nOutlets for the same doc page: left outputs \"<from> <to> <count>\" after each recorded transition; right outputs a node id when a new node is created."
				}

			}
